. 
<typeStatus box="[484,534,1339,1360]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Crawford" authorityName="Crawford" box="[627,975,1338,1360]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Aeolothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[627,868,1338,1360]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Aeolothrips vespiformis</emphasis>
Crawford
</taxonomicName>
, by monotypy.
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1405,2006]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">
Wing fully developed. Head usually partly retracted into prothorax and slightly prolonged anteriorly, with no long setae; fore ocellus about half the diameter of hind ocelli (
<figureCitation box="[839,928,1441,1466]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–84" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,245,1847]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 80–84. Franklinothrips oblongus sp. n., female: (80) Head &amp; pronotum (sculpture on pronotum omitted); (81) Antenna; (82) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum (sculpture on mesonotum omitted); (83) Tergites VIII–X (sculpture omitted); (84) Sternites VI–VII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2588940/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Fig. 80</figureCitation>
). Compound eyes prolonged ventrally with enlarged ommatidia. Maxillary palps 3-segmented, segment III short. Antennal segments III–IV long and slender, with elongate and sinuous or multifaceted sensoria, III at least 8 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[1130,1213,1513,1538]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–84" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,245,1847]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 80–84. Franklinothrips oblongus sp. n., female: (80) Head &amp; pronotum (sculpture on pronotum omitted); (81) Antenna; (82) Mesonotum &amp; metascutum (sculpture on mesonotum omitted); (83) Tergites VIII–X (sculpture omitted); (84) Sternites VI–VII." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2588940/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
). Pronotum without long setae. Mesonotum with median pair of setae medially. Metascutum almost smooth medially; with median pair of setae near posterior margin. Fore wing slender, costal vein with fringe cilia but no setae (
<figureCitation box="[1170,1253,1585,1610]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–24" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,194,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[340,1247,193,1925]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 15–24. Fore wings of Aeolothripidae, female. (15) Aeolothrips fasciatus; (16) A. fukushimensis sp. n.; (17) A. kurosawai; (18) A. luteolus; (19) A. melaleucus from Honshu; (20) A. setosus sp. n.; (21) A. vittatus; (22) Desmidothrips japonicus sp. n. (23) Franklinothrips oblongus sp. n.; (24) F. vespiformis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2588922/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
); clavus with 4– 7 veinal setae. Fore tarsus with recurved ventral hamus. Abdominal segments I–II more or less constricted in female; tergites II–VIII with S1 setae minute and wide apart; tergite X with paired trichobothria very small; sternites with 2 pairs of posteromarginal setae and 1–2 pairs of setae laterally in front of the margin; sternite VII with two pairs of accessary setae near posterior margin. Male tergite I with paired weak longitudinal ridges terminating in square or rounded apex overhanging tergite II.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="317" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1405,2006]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1801,1826]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Remarks</emphasis>
. Previously, this genus included 16 species, with six Neotropical, five Oriental, three Australasian and two Afrotropical, although species such as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Trybom" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[690,825,1837,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Franklinothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalops">
<emphasis box="[690,825,1837,1862]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">F. megalops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[883,1041,1838,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Aeolothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[883,1041,1838,1862]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">F. vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are widespread (ThripsWiki 2018; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Reynaud, P." box="[151,442,1873,1898]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref14639" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Reynaud, P. (2005) Franklinothrips; a pantropical Thysanoptera genus of ant-mimicking obligate predators (Aeolothripidae). Zootaxa, 864 (1), 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 864.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">Mound &amp; Reynaud 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Members of the genus are obligate predators and several species are ant-mimics. An identification key to 14 species is available (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Reynaud, P." box="[687,990,1909,1934]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref14639" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Reynaud, P. (2005) Franklinothrips; a pantropical Thysanoptera genus of ant-mimicking obligate predators (Aeolothripidae). Zootaxa, 864 (1), 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 864.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">Mound &amp; Reynaud 2005</bibRefCitation>
). This genus is closely related to the monotypic African genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1926" box="[446,643,1945,1970]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Corynothripoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[446,643,1945,1970]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Corynothripoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which may be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Back" authorityYear="1912" box="[988,1165,1945,1970]" class="Insecta" family="Aeolothripidae" genus="Franklinothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[988,1165,1945,1970]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="317">Franklinothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the later genus has head with the greater prolongation in front of compound eyes (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Reynaud, P." box="[853,1147,1981,2006]" pageId="16" pageNumber="317" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref14639" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Reynaud, P. (2005) Franklinothrips; a pantropical Thysanoptera genus of ant-mimicking obligate predators (Aeolothripidae). Zootaxa, 864 (1), 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 864.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">Mound &amp; Reynaud, 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
